atus><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E01061X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This postdoctoral project follows and expands upon doctoral research involving an ethnographic study of religious conversion amongst Dalit ('untouchable') slum dwellers in the South Indian city of Chennai. The conversion of Dalits out of Hinduism has long been a source of unease amongst the dominant (non-Dalit) population and especially amongst national elites, who frequently portray such conversions as an attack on a national culture, which they implicitly identify with Hinduism. This has led to a series of laws seeking to restrict and even ban certain types of religious conversion. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Where the doctoral project had considered a specific case of religious conversion amongst a dominated (or ?subaltern?) subpopulation, this postdoctoral research examines the broader political and historical context in which such conversions have been targeted by certain segments of the nation?s elite. Specifically, it seeks to systematically document the underlying assumptions about the nature of religion itself amongst Indian elites, and to pinpoint areas of divergence between elite and subaltern culture. This research will contribute to emerging research on the anthropology of secularism, and on the problems of regulating religions in the world?s largest multicultural democracy.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-06-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>69325</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/E01061X/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D21C7A3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Anthropology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D21C7A3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage